The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                               Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, March 23: The government has set up a committee to review the duty drawback rates at which the export sector is given tax refunds under different schemes. Under the duty drawback scheme, the finance ministry reimburses all central duties, including customs and central excise paid on inputs and service tax paid on input services used in the manufacture of export goods.                             
	 New Delhi, March 23: The government  alarmed by the 25 per cent rise in steel prices in the past three months  will seriously try to contain the prices, but the steel industry said regulating prices would affect growth. There is a need to contain prices which is possible by augmenting supplies through containment of exports, steel secretary Raghav Sharan Pandey said.                            
	 New Delhi, March 23: Sebi is likely to come out with the final guidelines on the self-regulatory organisation (SRO), the first-level regulator for the capital market, within three months. An SRO is a non-governmental body having statutory responsibility to regulate its own members for fair and efficient practices.                            
	 Mumbai, March 23: The Union Bank of India (UBI) plans to launch its reverse mortgage product by next month. The product is ready. The budget has cleared all the tax matters related to the product, UBI CMD M.V. Nair said.                            
	 Calcutta, March 23: Orthodox tea production is expected to touch 1,30,000 tonnes in the next five years, for which the government will provide a subsidy of Rs 100 crore.                                                                                                                           
